<strong>Is OpenStack Enough to Support NFV?<br>
Featuring: Red Hat</strong>
<br><br>
When seeking the best platform to enable Network Functions 
Virtualization, Service Providers have a major interest in using 
OpenStack and many have been testing OpenStack in their proof of concept
 environments. What most are finding is that OpenStack falls short in 
specific areas that are critical to their needs. 
<br><br>
OpenStack is not a network policy-aware solution: it lacks mechanisms to
 maintain policy-based application deployment, vertical/horizontal 
modeling, security and network insight; gaps can also be found with 
regards to placement and optimization of distributed resources, network 
integration, automated lifecycle management and infrastructure 
automation. Thus, an OpenStack-based design of a cloud infrastructure 
should include additional elements required for operational 
sustainability in a carriers’ network.
<br><br>
<a href="http://event.on24.com/eventRegistration/EventLobbyServlet?target=lobby.jsp&amp;eventid=835438&amp;sessionid=1&amp;key=6B029744A8794A4178115E96F657EE12&amp;eventuserid=102793249" _label="OpenStack">Listen to representatives from Red Hat and CloudBand</a>
 discuss the limitations of Open Stack and what we are doing through our
 joint collaboration to help get Service Provider requirements get 
noticed within the OpenStack community


